data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your test:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);  // or CollectionAssert.That is not built-in,
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User)); // type check
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // no built-in equivalent for predicates

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(x)` or keep `Assert.IsTrue` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(item))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same elements, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`

MSTest's `CollectionAssert` doesn't support predicate-based assertions natively (like "all items match condition"), so `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` is acceptable there — or consider adding **FluentAssertions** for richer syntax like `users.Should().OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`.
